Answer: \strong{1)} The best way \em{without} using `form` object, is to use event handlers combined with \em{vanilla} JS (vanillate) version of `requestFullScreen()` method:

\begin{blockquote}

\strong{The `requestFullscreen()` Method}

There is also a requestFullscreen() method for requesting full screen mode in supported browsers.
\end{blockquote}

\begin{code}
function activateFullscreen(elem) {
    let isSupported = (): boolean => {
        const elem = document.documentElement;
        return typeof elem.requestFullscreen === "function";
    }

    if (isSupported() && elem.requestFullscreen) {
        elem.requestFullscreen();
    }
}
\end{code}

\strong{2)} The problem with above approach is, that element is not added to it parent element (`form`) which means, that it can stay at current place or somewhere in the \em{DOM} flow (depending if form is opened e.g in new tab and `overflow: scroll;` property is set).

Example:

\begin{code}
const form = document.getElementById('form')

document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', e => {

  [...form.querySelectorAll("button")].forEach(element => {

    element.addEventListener('click',
      evt => {
        activateFullscreen(element)
        console.log(element.target);
      }
    );

  });
}
\end{code}

\begin{code}
#form {
  margin: 300px;
}
\end{code}

\begin{code}
<form action="">
  <input type="text"> <input type="submit" value="submit"> <button type="button" id="btn1"><button type="submit" id="btn2"> <button type="button" id="btn3">Cancel</button> </button>
</form>
\end{code}

\strong{3)} Another best way, is to use `form` object, in vanilla approach:

\begin{code}
function activateForm(form) {

    if (!form.can_activate) {
      form.can_activate = true;
      form.requestFullscreen();
    }

}
\end{code}

\begin{code}
<form action="">
  <input type="text"> <input type="button" value="submit"> <button type="button" id="btn1"><button type="submit" id="btn2"> <button type="button" id="btn3">Cancel</button> </button>
</form>
\end{code}

\strong{4)} The \em{vanillate} `activateFullscreen()` method (1) could be implemented by wrapping all event handlers with `requestFullScreen()` method, but it is not very elegant in my pov.
\begin{itemize}
\item \strong{5)} There is also a `Fullscreen.js` library which could help you get out of trouble:

https://github.com/codyhouse/Fullscreen.js

You could try:
\end{itemize}

\begin{code}
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Fullscreen.js Test</title>
    <script src="//code.jquery.com/jquery-latest.js"></script>
    <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/jquery.fullscreen/1.2.0/fullscreen.js"></script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <form id="form">
      <input type="text"> <input type="button" value="submit"> <button type="button" id="btn1"><button type="submit" id="btn2"> <button type="button" id="btn3">Cancel</button> </button>
    </form>
    <script type="text/javascript">
      $(document)
        .on('click', 'button', (e) =>
          {
            let id = 'form' + $(e.target).prop('id')
            Fullscreen.enter($('#' + id), {
              keyboard: true,
              forceFullscreen: true
            });
          }
        )
        .on('click', 'form', (e) => {
          $(document).find('button').prop('disabled', false);
          $('.btn-fullscreen').remove();
        }
        );
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
\end{code}

